ring 1368","1340":"1340","of Dudmaston, Shrpsh., Engl.":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"–":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1340–Male":"1340–Overleden","1368–Male":"1368–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1368":"1368","abt1368":"circa 1368","1340":"1340","of Dudmaston, Shrpsh., Engl.":"Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","1368–Male":"1368–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1368":"1368","abt1368":"about 1368","1340":"1340","of Dudmaston, Shrpsh., Engl.":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Upton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places in England called Upton, most of which are named with Old English <i>upp</i> ‘upper’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some have different origins, such as one in Essex, originally named with the phrase <i>upp in tūne</i> ‘up in the settlement’, i.e. the higher part of the settlement, and Upton Lovell (Wiltshire), which derives from the Old English personal name <i>Ubba</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>. This name was brought to Ireland (Antrim) in 1598 by Henry <i>Upton</i>, from Upton in Devon."],"variants":[{"name":"Uptain","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of English   Upton  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Upton was born as the daughter of Upton. She had at least 1 son with Roger Wolryche."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1368–Male":"1368–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1368":"1368","abt1368":"umbes 1368","1340":"1340","of Dudmaston, Shrpsh., Engl.":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1368–Male":"1368–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1368":"1368","abt1368":"noin 1368","1340":"1340","of Dudmaston, Shrpsh., Engl.":"Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1340–Male":"1340–Décédé","1368–Male":"1368–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1368":"1368","abt1368":"environ 1368","1340":"1340","of Dudmaston, Shrpsh., Engl.":"Shropshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Margaret Upton est née, fille de Upton. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Roger Wolryche."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1340–Male":"1340–Verstorben","1368–Male":"1368–Verstorben","–Male":"Verstorben","1368":"1368","abt1368":"um 1368","1340":"1340","of Dudmaston, Shrpsh., Engl.":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Margaret Upton wurde, als Tochter von Upton geboren. Sie hatte mit Roger Wolryche mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"–":"D